text: Cancer is one the leading cause of death worldwide and projected to continue rising with an estimate of 12 million deaths in 2030 (Jemal et al., 2010). Despite decades of investments and dedication of thousands of researchers, ﬁnding a cure for cancer is still a distant dream (Antonio and Shulze-Makuch, 2009). Tumors result from diﬀerent types of aberrations in the form of nucleotide base substitutions, deletions, chromosomal translocations and gene ampliﬁcations. The character- istics that set the cancer cells apart and known as the hallmarks of cancer are disregard for external and in- ternal control on proliferation, self suﬃciency in growth signals, avoid diﬀerentiation, angiogenesis, genetic in- stability, local and distant invasiveness (Hanahan et al., 2000). Cancer cells do survive both the natural and ar- tiﬁcial attempts to destroy them. Diﬀerent mechanisms to combat cancer are evolved with time, one such mech- anism is the development of therapeutics targeting spe- ciﬁc proteins and pathways. Cyclin dependent kinases Interdiscip Sci Comput Life Sci (2013) 5: 37–44 DOI: 10.1007/s12539-013-0146-0 Interaction of Marine Streptomyces Compounds with Selected Cancer Drug Target Proteins by in silico Molecular Docking Studies ∗Corresponding author. Abstract: The criteria currently followed for selecting antitumor compounds include agents that can target apoptosis inhibitor proteins and cancer cell markers. In silico studies are often used to identify suitable antitumor compounds for the cancer targets. The aim of the present study is to evaluate the interactions of some antitumor compounds reported from marine Streptomyces with cancer target proteins. Nine compounds were selected from marine Streptomyces based on previous reports and evaluated for their interactions with cancer target proteins by in silico molecular docking approach. Interactions of the selected ligand with target proteins were studied by PatchDock bioinformatics docking tool. Among the compounds tested marmycin A was interacted very eﬀectively with human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2) and showed a least binding energy of −472.92 kcal/mol. The compound altemicidin showed a least binding energy of −415.66 kcal/mol with cyclin dependent kinase 4 (CDK4). The ligands resistoﬂavine and resistomycin also interacted with HER2 and showed the binding energy of −402.10 kcal/mol and −377.78 kcal/mol respectively. Other ligands proximycin A, chandrananimycin C, echinosporin, streptochlorin and streptokordin also showed the binding energy of −341.11 kcal/mol, −313.31 kcal/mol, −305.64 kcal/mol, −291.91 kcal/mol and 222.34 kcal/mol respectively with CDK4 protein. These results of our study suggest that HER2 and CDK4 are better cancer drug targets for therapy. Key words: in silico molecular docking, PatchDock, marine Streptomyces, marmycin A, altemicidin, human epidermal growth factor receptor 2, cyclin dependent kinase 4. Amulya Ruby LANKAPALLI, K. (CDKs) are essential for the progression of cell cycle from one phase to the other. CDKs are a family of seri- nine/threonine kinases and are activated by complexes with their partners known as cyclins. The concentra- tion of cyclin varies during the diﬀerent phases of cell cycle. CDK1 is involved in G2/M transition and phos- phorylation of proteins that plays a vital role in the cell cycle. CDK2 binds with E-type and A-type cyclins and CDK4 and CDK6 complexes with cyclins D and E. CDK4 along with CDK6 is responsible for the phospho- rylation of retinoblastoma (RB) protein. CDKs 1, 7, 8, 9 phosphorylate the C-terminal domain of RNA poly- merase which carries out transcription. CDKs 7 and 9 are complexed with H-type cyclin and T1 cyclin respec- tively. Drugs such as R-roscovitine, e7070, astrazeneca are known inhibitors of CDK2 and PD 633991 is an inhibitor of CDK4 (Shah and Schwartz, 2006). The resistance of tumor cells to drug induced apop- tosis is a major setback in chemotherapy (Liu et al., 2011). Understanding the role of diﬀerent factors that prevent apoptosis and developing therapeutics target- ing these factors are focus of current research. The inhibitors of apoptosis are a family of proteins deﬁned by one or more conserved (70 amino acids) domains lo-

cated at the amino-terminus called Baculo-viral IAP re- peat and a conserved sequence termed ring ﬁnger (RF) in the carboxy domain. Eight IAPs have been identiﬁed in humans, XIAP, cIAP1, cIAP2, survivin, livin, bruce, NIAP, ILP-2. XIAP, cIAP1, cIAP2 and survivin di- rectly bind and inhibit caspases 3, 7, 9. XIAP has been well studied and has three domains BIR1, BIR2 and BIR3 and they are functionally distinct. BIR3 binds to the exposed region of caspase 9 after cleavage. BIR1 and BIR2 inhibit caspase 3 and 7. Bcl-2 is another family of anti-apoptotic proteins and 16 Bcl-2 protein homologues have been identiﬁed based on sequence similarity to the BH domains in Bcl-2. Bcl- Xl, Bcl-W, Mcl are anti-apoptotic, Bax, Bak, Bok, Bad, Bim, Bid and Noxa are capable of promoting apoptosis. These proteins are further divided into diﬀerent multi- BH domain proteins. The interactions between the BH3 domains of pro-apoptotic and anti-apoptotic proteins neutralize the anti-apoptotic functions of Bcl-2 and lead to apoptosis. Bcl-2 is over expressed in a wide variety of tumors. Antimycin A has been reported as an inhibitor of Bcl-2 and Bcl2-Xl (Rutledge et al., 2002). Cancer cells over express certain proteins which give them a growth advantage known as cancer cell markers. Cancer cell markers can be speciﬁc for certain types of cancers or sometimes the same marker can be over expressed in many cancers. Some of the cancer cell markers are HER-1, HER-2, HER-4, HCG and prostate speciﬁc antigen (PSA). These cancer cell markers play very important roles in cancer diagnosis while some are targeted in anti-cancer therapy (Lee et al., 2005).

Topoisomerases are essential for the survival of all eu- karyotic organisms and are highly conserved. Topoiso- merases are involved in DNA replication, chromosome condensation and chromosome segregation. Topoiso- merase I makes single strand breaks in the DNA while topoisomerase II makes double strand breaks. Ligase 4 is involved in homologous recombination and it seals the nicks of two DNA strands. More than 40 analogs of in- deno [1,2-c] isoquinoline have been synthesized to test their activity against topoisomerase I. Some of them were found to be potent inhibitors of topoisomerase I and showed acute cytotoxicity against number of tu- mour cells. A number of topoisomerase II inhibitors have been identiﬁed (Lansiaux and Pourquier, 2011). The bisdioxopiperazines (ICRF-193, ICRF-187 [dexra- zoxane] merbarone, and aclarubicin) are compounds that block the catalytic activity of DNA topoisomerase II but do not stabilize the DNA-topoisomerase II cleav- able complex. One promising therapeutic strategy for treating can- cer is to speciﬁcally target signal transduction path- ways that have a key role in oncogenic transformation and malignant progression. Hsp90 is an emerging ther- apeutic target of interest for the treatment of cancer. It is responsible for modulating cellular response to

stress by maintaining the function of numerous signal- ing proteins - known as ‘client proteins’ - that are asso- ciated with cancer cell survival and proliferation. Many cancers result from speciﬁc mutations in, or aberrant expression of, these client proteins. Hsp90 inhibitors (small molecules) bind to the ATP binding pocket, in- hibit chaperone function and could potentially result in cytostasis or cell death. Consequently, many client proteins are targeted for degradation via the ubiquitin- proteasome pathway including receptor and non recep- tor kinases (Erb-B2, epidermal growth factor receptor, and Src family kinases), serine/threonine kinases (c- Raf-1 and CDK4), steroid hormone receptors (androgen and estrogen), and apoptosis regulators such as mutant p53. Inhibition of Hsp90 function has also been proven eﬀective in killing cancer cells that have developed re- sistance to targeted therapies such as kinase inhibitors (Messauodi et al., 2008). The presence of excessive amount of heat shock proteins renders the cell resis- tance to apoptosis. Geldanamycin and 17-AAG have been found to inhibit HSP90 (Miyata, 2005). These two compounds are metabolised by NADH quinine oxi- doreductase, which is known to stabilize p53. However, the use of geldanamycin in clinical trials experienced many diﬃculties due to development of hepatotoxicity in human tumor models. Another drawback of these drugs is the activation HSP = 1, a transcriptional fac- tor of HSP-90 (Hanson and Vesole, 2009). VEGF is a signalling protein present in the cell that stimulates vasculogenesis and angiogenesis. The func- tion of VEGF is to create new blood vessels during embryonic development after injury, and to bypass the blocked blood vessels (Murakami, 2011). Hypoxia in- ducing factor (HIF-1) is a transcriptional factor and responds to the changes in the concentration of oxygen in the cell, especially during hypoxia.

Many novel metabolites are being discovered from marine sources. Marine ﬂoras, such as bacteria, acti- nobacteria, cyanobacteria, fungi, microalgae, seaweeds, mangroves, and other halophytes are extremely im- portant oceanic resources, constituting over 90% of the oceanic biomass. They are taxonomically diverse, largely productive, biologically active, and chemically unique oﬀering a great scope for discovery of new anti- cancer drugs. The marine ﬂoras are rich in medicinally potent chemicals predominantly belonging to polyphe- nols and sulphated polysaccharides. The chemicals have displayed an array of pharmacological properties especially antioxidant, immunostimulatory, and antitu- mour activities (Boopathy and Kathirasen, 2010). The genus Streptomyces is well known as the producer of new bioactive compounds and anti-tumor drugs (Dhar- maraj, 2010). With the advances in oceanographic studies new sources of Streptomyces with potential anti- tumor activity are being discovered (Olano et al., 2009). Recent developments in molecular characterization Interdiscip Sci Comput Life Sci (2013) 5: 37–44 and bioinformatics have further made it possible to “dock” small molecules (i.e. ligands) towards proteins and “score” their potential binding (Pripp, 2007). Protein-ligand docking is a molecular modeling tech- nique. The goal of protein-ligand docking is to pre- dict the position and orientation of a ligand (a small molecule) when it is bound to a protein receptor or en- zyme. Pharmaceutical research employs docking tech- niques for a variety of purposes, most notably in the vir- tual screening of large databases of available chemicals in order to select likely drug candidates. Thus methods like docking and virtual screening are becoming widely used in drug development (Pripp, 2007). In this study we report the interactions of compounds from marine Streptomyces with target proteins of diﬀerent types of cancer and amino acids involved in interactions with the ligand. Nine compounds from marine Streptomyces were se- lected as ligands (Table 1) based on anticancer ac- tivity reported previously. The compound marmycin A (Fig. 1(a)) was isolated by Martin et al. (2007) from marine-derived Streptomyces and has been shown to possess signiﬁcant cytotoxicity against several can- cer cell lines. Marmycin A was selected and docked with cancer target proteins and the least binding en- ergy was calculated. The other compound altemicidin (Fig. 1(b)) was isolated by Takahashi et al. (1989) from marine Streptomyces sioyaensis SA-1758 and reported to possess signiﬁcant anti-tumor and acaricidal activ- ity. The ligand altemicidin was docked with cancer target proteins and the least binding energy was calcu- lated. Other anti-tumor compounds (ligands) selected included resistoﬂavine (Gorajana et al., 2005), resis- tomycin (Jakobi and Hertweck, 2004), proximycin A (Fiedler et al., 2008), chandrananimycin C (Maskey et al., 2003), echinosporin (Cui et al., 2007), streptochlo- rin (Shin et al., 2007) and streptokordin (Jeong et al., Table 1 List of marine Streptomyces compounds (ligands) selected for docking studies 2006). Structures of the above anti-tumor compounds were downloaded in SDF format from Pubchem and were converted to PDB format by uploading in the E- Babel software. The chemical structure of the selected compounds was drawn using MODL ISIS 2.5 and saved as skc form.

Twenty proteins belonging to diﬀerent cancer types were selected as cancer targets for docking studies with selected ligands. The list of all target proteins selected for docking is given in Table 2. The 3D structure of all target proteins was downloaded from Protein Data Bank (PDB). The water molecules were removed during modeling. The standard protocol and modeling meth- ods were followed for docking studies. The energy min- imized protein structure was included prior to docking to accommodate hydrogen atoms and was not included in the crystal structure coordinates. 2.3 Functional site identiﬁcation functional sites in target proteins were performed based on Conserved Functional Group (CFG) analysis using siteFiNDER|3D server. It is a fully integrated, web-based implementation of the CFG analysis method for functional site prediction (Innis, 2007). 2.4 Molecular docking simulation In order to carry out the docking simulation Patch- Dock software available online was used as reported earlier (Jha et al., 2011). PatchDock is a molecu- In PatchDock surfaces of two lar docking algorithm. (a) Structure of marmycin; (b) Structure of al- temicidin in SDF format (Source: Pubchem, CID 6711682). Marmycin A R=H Marmycin B R=Cl molecules were divided into patches according to the surface shape. These patches correspond to patterns that visually distinguish between puzzle pieces. The identiﬁed patches were superimposed by using shape matching algorithms and veriﬁed by all three major stages which include molecular shape representation, surface patch matching and followed by ﬁltering and scoring. The protein and the ligand molecules obtained as PDB ﬁles were uploaded and submitted. It was run 20 solutions and out of which the solution with the high- est minimum energy was downloaded. All the docking runs were performed in Intel Pentium® D CPU@3.20 GHz of Lenovo think centre origin, with 2 GB DDR RAM. PatchDock was compiled and run under Linux operating system.

A quinine compound marmycin A belonging to an- gucycline was isolated from the culture broth of a ma- rine sediment-derived Streptomyces by Martin et al. (2007). The two new quinones marmycins A and B iso- lated were reported to be cytotoxic to cancer cells. The structure of the ligand marmycin A is given in Fig. 1(a). The interactions of marmycin A with diﬀerent cancer target proteins and their binding energies (kcal/mol) are given in Table 3. Marmycin A interacted strongly with HER2 protein and showed the least binding en- ergy of −472.92 kcal/mol (Fig. 2(a)). HER2 over expression results in increased HER2 containing dimers of all kinds. Increased HER2- EGFR dimers drive proliferative and invasive functions and increased HER2 homodimers disrupt cell polar- ity. Increased HER2-HER3 dimers drive proliferative, survival, invasive, and metabolic functions. Increased HER2 expression results in an increase in the rare Δ HER2 isoform with more potent signaling characteris- tics. Several transcription factors are induced in HER2 over expressed cells resulting in a plethora of gene expression changes leads to tumorogenesis (Moasser, 2007).

Takahashi et al. (1989) isolated an isoprenoid com- pound altemicidin from marine Streptomyces sioyaensis SA-1758 and reported to possess signiﬁcant anti-tumor and acaricidal activity. It has a monoterpene-alkaloid skeleton and the structure of altemicidin is given in Fig. 1(b). It was docked with selected cancer drug tar- get proteins and the binding scores obtained (kcal/mol) are given in Table 5. The compound altemicidin showed the least binding energy of -415.66 kcal/mol with cyclin dependent kinase 4 (CDK4) (Fig. 3(a)). Amino acids of CDK4 protein involved in the inter- action with altemicidin are shown in Fig. 3(b). The ligand altemicidin interacted with the following amino acids, TRP203, ALA210,ARG214, LEU218, PHE219, ILE231, LEU234, ILE235,GLY236, PRO259, ARG260, PRO261, VAL262 and GLN263 (Table 6). Altemicidin was found to inhibit the growth of murine lymphoid leukemia L1210 and carcinoma IMC cell lines with IC50 values of 0.84 and 0.82 µg/mL respectively. Other lig- ands docked with CDK4 protein also showed strong interaction and the binding energy was calculated for proximycin (−341.11 kcal/mol), for chandrananimycin C (−313.31 kcal/mol), for echinosporin (−305.64 kcal/mol), for streptocholorin (−291.91 kcal/mol), and for streptokordin (−222.34 kcal/mol) (Table 6).

The cyclin D-CDK4, 6/INK4/Rb/E2F pathway plays a key role in controlling cell growth by integrat- ing multiple mitogenic and antimitogenic stimuli. The components of this pathway are gene families with a high level of structural and functional redundancy and are expressed in an overlapping fashion in most tis- sues and cell types (Ortega et al., 2002). Cyclin de- pendent kinases (CDKs) are attractive targets for the development of pharmacological agents for the treat- ment of cancer. Recently, CDK family members that are not directly involved in cell cycle regulation have been identiﬁed. This includes CDK7, CDK8, and CDK9, which participate in transcription regulation, and CDK5, which plays a role in neuronal and secre- tary functions. Selective inhibitors are also needed as tools to explore the biology of diseases in which CDKs may participate and to develop therapeu- tics (Hirai et al., 2005).

Actinomycetes are the producers of a large number of natural products with diﬀerent biological activities, in- cluding anti -tumor properties. These anti-tumor com- pounds belong to several structural classes such as an- thracyclines, enediynes, indolocarbazoles, isoprenoides, macrolides, non-ribosomal peptides and others, and they exert anti-tumor activity by inducing apoptosis through DNA cleavage mediated by topoisomerase I or II inhibition, mitochondria permeabilization, inhi- bition of key enzymes involved in signal transduction like proteases, or cellular metabolism and in some cases by inhibiting tumor-induced angiogenesis (Olano et al., 2009). Out of the 9 compounds selected, 3 compounds showed interactions and strong binding with HER2 pro- tein and 6 compounds inhibited CDK4 target protein. Out of the 3 compounds marmycin A bound with least binding energy with HER2 protein. Similarly altemi- cidin bound to CDK4 with least binding energy. Thus our results validate the application of in silico studies to identify potential compounds and also to determine the appropriate targets for therapy. Based on the pre- diction of our study the eﬃcacy of marmycin A and altemicidin as an anticancer agent can be further con- ﬁrmed by in vivo studies.
